 					<p><exercise>
 						<statement>
 							<aside><p>((Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 3, Exercise 3.3.12)</p></aside>
 							If <m>A</m> is diagonalizable and <m>1</m> and <m>-1</m> are the only eigenvalues of <m>A</m>, show that <m>A^{-1} = A</m>.
 						</statement>
 						<solution>
 							<p> Write <m>A = PDP^{-1}</m>.  Then <me>A^{-1} = (PDP^{-1})^{-1} = (P^{-1})^{-1}D^{-1}P^{-1} = PD^{-1}P^{-1}</me>.  Since <m>D</m> is diagonal, <m>D^{-1}</m> is also diagonal, and for each <m>j</m> if the <m>(j,j)</m> entry of <m>D</m> is <m>d_{j,j}</m> then the <m>(j,j)</m> entry of <m>D^{-1}</m> is <m>1/d_{j,j}</m>.  We know that the diagonal entries of <m>D</m> are the eigenvalues of <m>A</m>, so by hypothesis they are all <m>\pm 1</m>, and hence <m>1/d_{j,j} = d_{j,j}</m> for all <m>j</m>.  Thus <m>D = D^{-1}</m>, so <me>A^{-1} = PD^{-1}P^{-1} = PDP^{-1} = A</me>.</p>
 						</solution>
 					</exercise></p>

